\begin_layout Section
Economical Models
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What an economical model actually is? Unlike physics, where there are very
 precise models that explain the exact behavior of all objects of interest
 by using strict rules and calculations, an economical model is not quite
 the same.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is no goal to actually predict and calculate the precise outcome.
 Hitting 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

in the vicinity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the result, or just determining the direction is usually good enoguh.
 Therefore, no need to put all the relevant data to the model.
 The opposit is true - try to add the least possible data, to highlight
 the specific relevant economic forces and understand them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There're 2 problmes we have to deal with:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We don't know all the forces existing in the economy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The economy might react to decisions (people have free will and try to increase
 their utility) - thus we can't assume people will always behave the same.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bottom line - in an economical model we try to capture the smallest amount
 of variable, which will give valuable insight.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Neo-Classical Framework
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Based on 2 assumptions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Prices are flexible.
 Every firm can ask any price for a product, any employee and employer can
 negotiate, there is no max or min price imposed by the government.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Prices are in an equilibrium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider a 
\series bold
closed
\series default
 economy, meaning no import/export and no free movement of labor or goods
 (i.e North Korea, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Island Economy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, etc).
 Obviously it is a very simplified case, yet it still provides important
 insights.
 Usually, large economies are less open (<10% GDP are import/export in the
 US).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Only a 
\series bold
single
\series default
 good is in consideration.
 The good must be 
\series bold
perishable
\series default
 - if it is not consumed, it is wasted and cannot be saved anymore.
 Thus, there's no point it producing more than can be consumed.
\end_layout

