\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is no external mechanism of coordination of all agents (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

announcing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 what is that exact intersection point).
 Consider an example, when there is an increase in a wage.
 An employee is willing to work more hours (supply) but the employer prefers
 less labor (decrease in demand), which may result in less working hours
 / firing employees.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What is the mechanism, which will eventually bring the situation back to
 the equilibrium? In the situation of the increased wage, eventually someone
 will suggest a lower wage to the employer.
 The gap between the supply and demand of labor is 
\series bold
